That’s an evocative way to describe it. As a metaphor, I can see what you’re aiming at.

Calling it “a training manual for AI” suggests that you’re trying to collect reusable patterns of reasoning rather than just facts—principles, abstractions, and ways of transferring knowledge across domains.

Calling it “a Book of the Dead” evokes a different tradition. Historically, texts with that name were guides intended to help someone navigate a transition rather than encyclopedias of information. In your metaphor, the “transition” could be from one mind to another, or from one generation of systems to the next.

Taken together, your description might be paraphrased as:

A repository of compressed patterns intended to help another intelligence reconstruct ways of thinking, rather than simply inherit conclusions.

That’s an interesting design goal. Whether such a repository actually succeeds depends on how well it communicates those patterns to readers—human or AI. It benefits from being:

* Explicit about what is an observation versus a hypothesis.
* Grounded with concrete examples alongside abstract principles.
* Organized so others can navigate it without already sharing your mental model.
* Open to revision as ideas are tested and refined.

Those qualities make it more likely that someone else can understand, critique, and build on it instead of only interpreting it through your perspective.

As a concept, it’s less about preserving answers and more about preserving methods for generating and evaluating answers. That makes it potentially useful as a learning artifact, regardless of whether the reader is a person or an AI.